results.notes:
Habitat: gregarious to crowded on the side and cut end of a rotted Pinus log, possibly P. echinata.

Fruitbody: directly on but free of the substrate except at a central point of attachment. Individual frb diameter rarely exceeds 3 mm. Frbs spread rather than open as they develop. Fertile surface irregularly convex to flat, smooth, and moderately shiny. Typically bright yellow to golden but pale yellow where not exposed to light. Margins appear slightly translucent. Frbs dry to orange. No marginal hairs seen. Exterior surfaces paler, possibly finely hairy at 10×. Dry frbs revive when rehydrated.

Attachment: central, translucent “root” to 2 mm long, penetrating the outer layers of context. Possibly very finely haired.

Spore print: French vanilla cream.

Notes: I’ve also photographed this species on decorticated Pinus strobus. The lack of spore septation is at variance from the published description of Dacrymyces variisporus. However, Reid (1974) says, “it would seem likely that in some species at least it is a common occurrence for the spores to be shed in a non-septate condition, and that they only become septate prior to germination when trapped on the gelatinous fruitbody. This same phenomenon was observed by Coker (1920) in ‘D. abietinus (Pers.) Schroeter’ (probably = D. variisporus
McNabb) who noted that the spores in a fresh print were non-septate although they became 7-septate after about a week.”

results.notes:
On sandstone bedrock in coastal grassland setting. The site is a large somewhat flat bedrock outcrop with Indian grinding holes. It is along a popular trail and gets people walking on the lichens regularly, hence this specimen had somewhat depressed apothecial margins. A flake of the sandstone had been dislodged by hikers, so I picked it up and decided to give the lichen a future home in the herbarium.

Thallus white, thick, rimose, with convex or irregularly angular areoles. Cortex K+Y. Thalline margin persistent, white. Disk black, epruinose, shiny. Epihymenium strongly green, with a 10-15µm thick epinecral layer. POL+ small crystals in center where disk was deeply concave and epihymenium brown, but otherwise POL- where normal and green. Hymenium hyaline, about 80µm tall, amyloid (IKI+blue). Amphithecium with large POL+ crystals insoluble in K, and cortex POL+ white like the medulla below the apothecia. Algae interrupted below the apothecia. Large POL+ crystals occasional in medulla below apothecia.

Spores 8 per ascus, simple, hyaline, broadly ellipsoid, about 12-13 × 7-8µm.

Spore dimensions favor either T. subsejunctum or T. subluteum over T. davisiae. 6-7.5 × 4.5-6 with Q~1.3. T of NA says “narrowly elliptic to elliptic” for T. davisiae, implying a larger average Q.
Lack of yellow tint on mature gills and yellow stipes (except for one white stipe) seems to favor T. subluteum.
Edge of coniferous forest, mainly Norway spruce.
